  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite its publication in 2020, \"Strategic Imaginations\" has shown limited scholarly uptake, with no recorded citations or mentions across high-fidelity social platforms. However, its potential commercial relevance is indicated by its presence on major commercial platforms like Amazon and Goodreads.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Published by Leuven University Press in 2020, \"Strategic Imaginations\" represents an academic exploration likely aimed at informing debates around strategic thinking. However, as of now, the book has not accrued any citations, indicating that its influence within the academic landscape remains nascent. With zero downloads or mentions on community platforms such as Wikipedia, Reddit, and Bluesky, the book has not yet stimulated public or community discourse.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite the apparent lack of visibility in both academia and public arenas, the work maintains a strong commercial connection, suggested by its listings on platforms like Amazon and Goodreads. This presence indicates that the book may attract readers beyond the scholarly community, potentially reaching a wider audience interested in the subject of strategic thinking.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">A notable strength of \"Strategic Imaginations\" lies in its alignment with sustainability and policy relevance, as inferred from its classification pertaining to sustainable development goals. This suggests that the content may resonate with contemporary discussions on societal and environmental issues, even if not yet realized in public discourse.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Looking towards future engagement, it is essential for authors and publishers to consider strategies for enhancing the visibility of works like \"Strategic Imaginations.\" Through targeted outreach and participation in relevant discourse communities, there is potential for the book to contribute meaningfully to both academic and public discussions related to strategic thinking and its implications for policy and practice.</p>",
